{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2goncharova_ver03/data/sn83045462/0028060513A/1948102401/0116.xml":{"full_text":"Injuries Are Fatal\nTo Woman Hit by\nStreetcar Thursday\nMis* Alice Anderson. 38, of 1499\nIrving street N.W., died last night\nat Emergency Hospital of injuries\nreceived Thursday when she was j\nstruck by a streetcar on Fourteenth\nstreet N.W., near her home.\nMiss Anderson, a secretary with\nthe Civil Aeronaqtics Board, was\nthe District's 54th traffic fatality of\nthe year, as compared with 59 at\nthis time in 1947.\nPolice said the operator of the\nstreetcar which struck Miss Ander\nson was Homer H. Glaves, 52, of\n1820 Lamont street N.W.\nIn critical condition last night at\nCasualty Hospital was Miss Loretta\nM. Ratell, 39, of Indian Orchard.\nMass., whose reunion with a cousin\nshe hadn\u2019t seen in 15 years was sad\ndened when the car in which they\nwere riding collided with a streetcar.\nPlanned Visit Often.\nPolice said Miss Ratell had\nplanned often to visit her cousin,\nMrs. Aurore Firebaugh, wife of Lt.\nComdr. Gordon E. Firebaugh, who\nis stationed at Patuxent, Md. Some\nthing always prevented the meet\ninc\nYesterday, however, Miss Ratell\narrived at Union Station, and\nComdr. and Mrs. Firebaugh were\nthere to meet her. The three left\nthe station, and, at Delaware ave\nnue and C streets N.E., their car\ncollided with a streetcar operated\nby Reese J. Applewhite, 62, of 6737\nRoosevelt avenue, Seat Pleasant, po\nlice said.\nMiss Ratell received a fractured\nright arm and internal injuries.\nMrs. Firebaugh, 35, was admitted at\nCasualty for treatment of chest in\njuries, and her husband, 37, was\ntreated for cuts and bruises.\n16 Hurt in Accidents.\nSixteen persons were injured, one\ncritically in three accidents in near\nby Maryland yesterday and last\nnight.\nMost seriously hurt was Mis.\nGertrude R. Ressjng, 74, of 103 Mel\nbourne avenue. Silver Spring, who\nwith seven others, was injured in\na four-car crash on the Baltimore\nboulevard at Muirkirk, yesterday.\nShe was admitted to the Leland\nMemorial Hospital, Riverdale, where\nher injuries were diagnosed as a j\nbroken left leg, a bAjken left arm,\nsevere head cuts, undetermined in\nternal injuries and shock. Her\ncondition was described as very:\ncritical.\nAdmitted to the same hospital\nwere Mrs. Ressing\u2019s granddaughter,\nMrs. Jane Minor, 28, of the Silver\nSpring address, and the latter\u2019s hus\nband. Lucien B. Minor, 31. Both\nsuffered several broken ribs and j\ncut* and bruises on the head and\nbody. All were riding in Mr. Minor\u2019s j\ncar.\ni\nTwo Soldiers Injured.\nTwo Fort Meade soldiers riding in\nan Army staff car were taken to!\nthe Leland Hospital and then trans\nferred to the Fort Meade hospital.\nThey were Pfc. Lloyd Barrnon, 22,\nand Pvt. James Page. Mr. Barrnon,\ndriver of the car, suffered a broken\nJaw, head concussion and cuts and\nbruises. Mr. Page suffered multiple\ncuts and bruises.\nA family of three riding in a third\ntar involved in the accident also\nwere injured but released after treat\nment at the Riverdale Hospital.\nThey were James Morgan, 25, West.,\nStewarts town, N. H.; his wife, Kath\nerine, 25, and their daughter, Carol\nLee, 2. All were treated for cuts and\nbruises.\nMaryland State Trooper Ernest!\nE. Hudgins reported the accident j\noccurred when the Army car appar\nently went out of control and skid\nded on the wet highway into the rear j\non an automobile driven by Melvin\nT. Houk, 29, of 809 Mount Vernon\nplace N.W.\nThe careening' car then turned\ncompletely around and was struck\nfrom the rear by Mr. Minor's car,\nwhich suffered the brunt of the!\ncrash. It then continued skidding\nacross the highway where it was\nstruck by Mr. Morgan's car, Troop- j\ner Hudgins said.\nNeither Mr. Houk or his wife were\ninjured.\nFive persons were injured yester-!\nday in an accident on the Columbia\npike yesterday near White Oak.\nThose taken to Walter Reed Hos\npital and their injuries were Terry\nA. Frazier, 35, of 2001 Powhatan\nroad, Hyattsville, driver of one car,\nloss of several teeth and a cut\nmouth; Maj. James A. Boole, 30, of\nWalter Reed Hospital, sprained\nankle and cuts and bruises on his\nneck and face; Mary A. Pickering,j\n37, Montgomery road, Laurel, bruised\nleft shoulder; and Thomas W.\nLloyd, 41, Montgomery road, Laurel,\nsevere head cuts. Wallace L. Faust.'\njr\u201e 26, of Laurel, driver of the\nsecond car in which the other two\nLaurel residents were riding, suf\nfered chest injuries and was taken,\nto the Washington Sanitarium.\nSkidding is Blamed.\nMontgomery County police said\nthe accident occurred when Mr.\nFrazier's car skidded and struck\nby Mr. Faust\u2019s car. Both drivers;\nwere charged with reckless driving\nand released on their personal bond\npending hearings in Silver Spring\nPolice Court at 10 a m. November 9.\nThree persons were hurt in a two\ncar collision on the Baltimore boule\nvard, near Beltsville, last night.\nTreated at Leland Hospital were\nLonnie Isley, 33. colored, of Balti\nmore, driver of the first car and his\nW\u2019ife, Vivian, 33, who suffered mul\ntiple cuts and bruises: and Mrs.\nAnna Hicfcs. 19, of Kenilworth, Md.,\nwho suffered face cuts.\nMrs. Hicks husband. Walter, 22,\ndriver of the other car, and their\nbaby boy were uninjured. State\nTrooper Robert Wolfe charged both\nwith reckless driving and released\nthem on personal bond. A hearing\nwas set for Hyattsville Police Court\nNovember 4.\nPopulation Gains Vary\nDuring the depression 30s in the\nUnited States the population of the\nNew England States increased 3.3\nper cent, the Middle Atlantic States\n4.9 per cent and the Pacific States\n18.8 per cent. _\nCUSTOM\nBUILDERS\nWe are in position to begin im\nmediate construction of custom\nbuilt hordes, apartments or\ncommercial buildings. 25 years1,\nexperience.\nComult ut, no obligation.\nTRIANGLE ENGINEERING\nSUPPLY CO.\nOR. 5877 SH. 9291\nPETER J. PETRAKOS.\nTHEODORE C. LINK.\nEarl Shelton.\nJack Axhby.\nRay Walker.\nPEORIA, ILL.\u2014REPORTER CHARGED IN KIDNAPING\u2014A Pe\noria County grand Jury yesterday indicted Mr. Link, reporter\nfor the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, together with Shelton, Ashby\nand Walker, on a charge of Intimidation, conspiracy and kid\nnaping in their \u201cquestioning\u201d of Peter Petrakos, Peoria punch\nboard operator and former associate of the late Bernie Shelton,\nSouthern Illinois gangster. \u2014A. P. Wirephotos.\nShelton\n(Continued Fro\u00ae First Page.)\ntrial and will defend him to the last\nditch.\u201d\nMr. Link, 43, an investigative re\nporter for the Post-Dispatch whose\ncontacts include gamblers and gang\nsters, was assigned to investigate the\nambush killing of Bernie Shelton\nin Peoria July 26.\nIn one story, he wrote that an\nemissary for Mr. Hull attempted to\nsolicit a $25,000 bribe from Bernie\nShelton in exchange for dropping\nan assault charge pending against\nShelton. He said a recording had\nbeen made and kept of the con\nversation between Shelton and the\nalleged emissary. Mr. Hull, who\nsubsequently was indicted for At\ntempted bribery, denied the charge.\nNewspaper Censured.\nThe grand jury in its report today\nsaid:\n\"It is incumbent on us as a grand\njury tfe censure the St. Louis Post\nDispatch for its publication of al\nlegations and charges which must\nbe judged in the light of the evi\ndence to have been calculated to\nserve other purposes than of either\ntruth or the public good.\n\"Further censure must attach\nspecifically to Mr. Link for his\npart in the publication of these\ncharges and allegations and more,\nparticularly for his avoidance of\nservice to appear before this grand\nJury.\n\"The evidence tends to show -that\nLink relied for the information\nwhich he published in the state\nments, unsupported and unworthy\nof belief, of self-admitted gamblers,\nbrothel-keepers, prostitutes, ex-con\nvicts and others of like stripe.\u2019\u2019\nAll four men were named in three\nindictments. The conspiracy in-'\ndictment contained seven counts:\nthe kidnaping two. and the intimi-1\ndation 22.\nFinds No Gambling Evidence.\nThe September grand jury said It;\nheard no evidence to support the\nearlier grand jury\u2019s statement that\nit had been told arrangements were\nready for resumption of open gam\nbling in Peoria and the county after\nthe November 2 elections.\nTlie earlier grand jury said It\nbelieved there was widespread gam\nbling and a tie-in between racketeers\nand gamblers in Peoria and recom\nmended a continuation of the In\nvestigation by a later grand jury.\nBond was set at $11,000 each for\nthe four men. No date for a hear\ning has been set.\nThe Post-Dispatch late today pub\nlished a letter written by Verle W.\nSaflord, special prosecutor, who di\nrected the previous Peoria County j\ngrand 'jury that indicted Mr. Hull,\nSheriff Earl Spainhower and Charles\nSomogyi, Mr. Hull\u2019s investigator.\nThey were accused of malfeasance,\nin addition to the attempted brib\nery charge against Mr. Hull alone.\nLetter Published.\nMr. Safford\u2019s letter said in part::\n\u201cI want to thank your pub-i\nlication and particularly your mast\nable reporter, Theodore L. Link, for\nthe manner in which you have\ncovered these proceedings.\n\u201d1 have only the finest expression\nto speak on behalf of Mr. Link.\u201d\nMr. Link, a native of St. Louis,\nformerly was special investigator\nfor the National Lead Co. in sili\ncosis law suits. He also previously\nwas a reporter on the St. Louis\nStar-Times. He joined the Post\nDispatch staff in 1938 and has been\nthere since. Except for three years\nin the Marines during the war.\nAttorney General Barrett\u2019s office i\nalso conducted ap investigation of\ncomplaints of vice, gambling and j\ncorruption in the Springfield (111.) J\narea.\nThat Grand Jury reported two\ndays ago. It returned no indict\nments and found \"alleged charges\nof payment of graft to public\nofficials as well as acts of misfeas\nance and malfeasance are absolutely\nwithout foundation.\"\nHowever, the jurors said there was\nevidence of \"criminal commercial\n1\nDutch Boy Blended Paint\nBlended paint la\nsomething new on\nthe surface. It Is\nDutch Boy makers\ngreatest achieve- gw\nment. It's like this\u2014\nthey\u2019ve blended a\npaint for every pur- MAIISI OIJUT\npose\u2014of the finest w\u00bb\u201cs\u00ab twnI\noils and pigments.\nIt's so good\u2014that Dutch Boy says: This\npaint will put a smile ot beauty on your\nhouse and keep It there. See the color\ncard at\nChevy Chase Paint Hardware Ca.\nSilver Spring Paint Hardware Co.\nBethesda Paint A Hardware Co.\nTakoma Paint A Hardware Co.\nBecker Paint A Glass Co.. Georgetown\nlaical Paint A Hardware Co., Hyattsvlllo\n922 New York Ave. (1) NA. 8610\nOpen Mon. thrp Sat.. a.m. to A:3# a.m.\n1 Free Parking Next Door While Trading Here\nlzed gambling\u201d in Springfield and\nSangamon County. The Jury rec\nomended prosecution of 11 persons\nit identified with illegal punchboard,\npin ball and horse race betting op\nerations.\nAt St. Louis, the Post-Dispatch,\ni commenting editorially, said in\n1 part:\n\"The indictment at Peoria of\nTheodore C. Link, reporter for the\nPost-Dispatch, is an irresponsible\nact inspired by desperate men.\ni \u201cIt is an act brought on by faith\ni less politicians who know that a\nday of reckoning for their misrule\nin Illinois is at hand.\n\u201cIt is an act designed to use the\nprocesses of the law, not to serve\nthe cause of justice as the law in\ntends. but to obstruct justice.\nNewspaper Welcomes Teat.\ni \u201cIt is an act which will deceive\nno one who knows the facts j\n\"Mr. Link has spent many weeks\nin Illinois getting facts about the\ndegradation of local and State gov\nernment. He will go back to Peoria\nvoluntarily. The Post-Dispatch wel\ncomes any test State's Attorney\nHull and Attorney General Barrett\ncare to make on their empty in\ndictment.\n\u201cCowardly men in Illinois are\nwatching the clock as the hour hand\nmoves toward Election Day. Novem\nber 2. They think they can muzzle\nthe Poet-Dispatch. They are wrong\nand their effort should prove thdjr\nundoing.\n\u201cThe Post-Dispatch will not be\nI intimidated. It will not be gagged.\u201d!\nDeficiency\n_^Continued From First Page.i\npermit early letting of a contract\nfor construction of the station house.\nIf Congress approves the deficiency,\nsum for the station house, Mr. Hut-;\nson declared, construction can begin\nby March, 1949. District officials\nfigure the job can be done in nine:\nmonths, Which would permit the\npolice to vacate the school annex\nand move in at the new station\nhouse by January, 1950.\nThis arrangement would be per\nfectly satisfactory to both police\nand school officials, since the second\nsemester of the public school year\u2019\nbegins in February of each year.\nThe smallest item\u2014$00,000 for the\ni municipal garage, Constitution ave\nnue and John Marshall place N.W.\n\u2014was made vital, District officials\u2019\nsaid, by an accident last week when\nthe remaining automobile elevator\nwent out of control and rushed1\nwildly toward the roof. A garage\nemploye on the elevator barely\nmanaged to jump to saiety.\nElevators Too Small.\nIn addition, both elevators were\nmade when automobiles were not\nas long as they now are. according\nto Col. Cox. Some city-owned auto\nmobiles, including a number of Po\nlice Department vehicles, have to\nbe dismantled partially before they\ncan be fitted onto the elevator plat- j\nforms for transportation to higher\nfloors at the garage.\nIf Congress approves the defi\nciency sum for a new elevator, Mr.\nHutson said, it will be placed on the\noutside of the building instead of\ninside where the present elevators\nare located.\nHealth Department officials al\nready have decided to ask the Com\nmissioners for a deficiency appro\npriation of $102,742 to pay three\nWashington hospitals for treating\nindigent patients during the fiscal\nyear ended June 30. The money\nremains unpaid because of an in\nsufficient congressional appropria\ntion.\nThe three hospitals\u2014Children\u2019s.\nEmergency and Casualty\u2014submitted\ncharges totalling $422,742 but avail-1\nable appropriations covered only\n$320,000.\nC. U. Alumni Hear\nArchbishop O'Boyle\nStress Education\nThe Most Rev. Patrick A. O\u2019Boyle,\narchbishop of Washington, told 600\nmembers of the Catholic University\nAlumni Association last night that\nthe most serious challenge to the\nchurch today is in the field of\nj education.\nThe archbishop addressed a re\nunion banquet of the association,\nthe first to be held in Washington,\nat the Hotel Statler.\nThe reunion program ends today\nwith a memorial mass at 11 a.m. in\nGibbons Hall Chapel and a meet ing\not the boat'd of governors.\nLargest Enrollment in History,\ni Archbishop O\u2019Boyle said the\nasnwer to the challenge on the\n'score of education is first, for the\nchurch to provide the best educa\ntion for both the ministers and lay\nmen. Secondly, he said, alumni of\nCatholic colleges \u201chave an obliga\ntion to place their intelligence in\nthe service of Christ.\u201d\nThe Rt. Rev. Msgr. Patrick J. Mc\nCormick, rector of the university,\ntold the alumni the institution this\nyear has the largest enrollment in\nits history\u20144,645.\nNicholas J. Chase, president of the\nWashington alumni chapter, opened\nthe program that followed dinner.\nRichard W. Galiher, chairman of\nthe reunion committee, presided.\nCites Football Defeat.\nEdmund R La Pond, director of\nathletics, another speaker, began:\n\"It's been a tough day\u201d\u2014a reference\nto Catholic University\u2019s defeat by\nJohns Hopkins yesterday at football.\n\"But,\u201d he continued, \"there /were\n700 teams playing today, and only\nhalf of them won. And we're doing\nit a whole lot cheaper.\"\nThe last was an allusion to the\npolicy of no athletic scholarships.\nThe president of the alumni or\nganization, Andrew P. Maloney of\nj New York, introduced Archbishop\n:O'Boyle. Mr. Maloney was.present\ned a desk set by Charles P. Maloney\nof Washington, former president, on\nbehalf of the Washington chapter.\nLewis L. Guarnieri of Warren,\nOhio, was re-elected president of\nlaw alumni at a meeting yesterday.\nHerman W. Kegebein\nFound Dead in Home\nHerman W. Kegebein. 60, said by\nfellow officers to have been the last\nMetropolitan policeman to patrol a\nbeat on a horse, was found dead yes\ni terday at the foot of a stairway in\nhis home at 2837 Brentwood road\nN.E.\nAn autopsy will be performed to\nday to determine whether Mr. Kege\nbein died from striking his head on\na stair or as a result of a heart\nattack. He was found by a cousin,\nElmer Wildman. 1831 Second street\nN.E., after Mr. Kegebein's wife, who\nwas away at the time, reported she\ncouldn't get a response to telephone\ncalls to the home. Mrs. Kegebein\nhad spent the night at the home of\nher daughter. Mrs- Margaret Sandy,\nLandover Hills, Md.\nMr. Kegebein was born and edu-1\ncated in Lansing, 111. He was in the\ncavalry at Fort Myer for several;\nyears before he joined the force in\n1919. He went to No. 12 precinct\nin 1924 as a mounted policemen, and\nfriends there said he was the last\nso assigned in the department.\nFor six years prior to retiring in\n1944, Mr. Kegebein was in charge of\nthe, school boy patrols in No. 12\nprecinct.\nMr. Kegebein grew flowers as a\nhobby. He planted rose bushes\naround the precinct station at\nSeventeenth street and Rhode Is\nland avenue N.E., and cared for\nthem until his retirement.\nBesides his widffw, Mrs. Amelia\nKegebein, and his daughter, he is\nsurvived by brothers wild sisters in\nLrnsing and two granddaughters.\nFuneral arrangements have not\nbeen completed.\nWarren Will Attend Rally\nIn Oakland and Vote There\n\u25a0y tht Aitsciatcd Pratt\nSACRAMENTO, Calif., Oct. 23\nGov. Earl Warren plans to do hi*\nvoting November 2 in Oakland,\nwhere he began his political career\nas an assistant district attorney.\nThe Republican vice presidential\ncandidate is scheduled to attend an\nelection eve rally in Oakland and\nvote there early the next morning.\nHe has not decided whether to\nawait returns in Oakland or Sacra\nmento.\nGov. Warren has an intensive\nCalifornia campaign tour ahead of\nhim. He plans no speeches tomor\nrow, however. He will rest at the\nexecutive mansion here with his\nfamily.\nRifes to Be Held Tomorrow;\nFor Mrs. Mary Palmer\nFuneral services will be held at\n2:30 p.m. tomorrow for Mrs. Mary\nM. Palmer, 73, life-long Washington\narea resident, who died at her home\nFriday after an illness of several\nyears. She lived at 6307 Eads street,\nSeat Pleasant.\nThe rites will be in the Deal\nFuneral Home, 816 H street N.E.;\nBurial will be in Rock Creek- Ceme- j\ntery. _\nMrs. Palmer was born in Wash-\ningtort and lived in Seat Pleasant\nmore than 40 years. Her husband,\nJoseph M. Palmer, who died in 1941,\nwas a Navy Yard employe.\nFREE! This Book\nMAIL TODAY!\nCRII DIAPER SERVICE. Dept. S\n21-31 Pierce St N W r,,t* vrnny\ni' 31 n*rce il r, TT- postcard or en\nWoshington 1. D C. in\nPlease send me \"WHO-MIt\"\nBooklet FREE\nNAME_\nAddress _\nCity_ State_\nI Phone Number_\n^Approx Date Expectinr_\nA GIFT TO BE PRIZED\nBY MOTHERS-TO-BE\nYES! Crib Diaper Service otters the\nexpectant mother another service\nIt you are expecting a little\none here is an' unusual baby book\nwith IKilO baby names, horoscopes,\nbirthstones. flowers and other at\ntractive baby Ideas. This book is\ns FREE to mother<-lo-be who reside\nr in Washington and the suburbs.\nJust All out the coupon below and\n1 mall today!\nWashington's Finest\nI\nI\nI\nI DI*PER SERVICE\n21-31 Pierce St. N.W.\nWashington 1, D. C.\nPhone ME. 1452\nJ Two Dolivoriea Woeklyl\nPleaee include expectancy month, to that\nw\u00ab can include correct Horoicope Booklet.\nTwo WAFs From District Area\nBegin Basic'Airman' Training\nMiss Glenna Allen (left) and Miss Mary Irene Webster\nshown in their new WAF uniforms At Lackland Air Force Base,\nTex. \u2014U. S. A. F. Photo\nBy Harriet Griffiths\nTwo young vtomen from the\nWashington area are leading the\ndisciplined life of \"airmen\u201d at\nLackland Air Force Base, Tex., as\nmembers of the newly created j\nWomen in the Air Force.\nThe two, Miss Mary Irene Web\ntster, 23, of 2504 North Fourth street.\nArlington, and Miss Glenna M.\ni Allen, 24, formerly of 906 Green\nstreet, Alexandria, are among the\nfirst group of WAFs to begin their\nbasic training at the huge San An\ntonio base.\nAlong with their fellow \"basics,\u201d\nMiss Webster and Miss Allen are,\nlearning a way of life entirely new\nto them\u2014that of members of the\nAir Force.\nAnd military discipline has no use\nfor dawdling or temperament. But\nboth girls are surprised at the feel\ning of accomplishment the end of a\nday can bring.\nDrilling Favorite Activity.\nMiss Allen at any moment can\ndisplay a foot locker as neat as the\naccounts she kept for the American\nRed Cross before she joined the\nWAF. She had lived in Alexandria\nsince September, 1942. Her sister\nand brother, both of that city, are\nMrs. F. M. Milam, 159 Williams\nstreet, and Hubert L. Allen, 3501\nWilson avenue.\nDrilling is her favorite WAF\nactivity so far. Eventually, she\nwould like to get into recruiting\nor be a hostess on military flights.\nMiss Webster, daughter of Maj.\nand Mrs. Daniel Webster, joined\nthe WAF because her father \"got\nall enthused about it\u201d. She was\nthe first WAF to be accepted. Maj.\nWebster, now with the Air Force\nin Tokyo, formerly was stationed*\nat the Pentagon.\nMiss Webster worked for the Army\nMap Service in Washington before\nbecoming a WAF. She prefers the\nadministrative end of the service, i\nhaving a background in library\nwork.\nGet Up At 6.\nThe WAP \u201cbasics\u201d arise at 6\na m. By 6:15, they are in formation\nfor the march to breakfast. After\nbreakfast until 10 minutes of 6\nthey \u201cpolice\u201d the barracks, and then\nbegin their daily classes.\nSupper is at 6 p.m\u201e and the girls\nare free until \u201clights out\u201d at 9 pm.\nThey sleep two in a room in the i\nWAP barracks.\nThe classes include physical train\ning, which Brig. Gen. Charles F.\nBorn, commanding general of the\nIndoctrination Division, believes\nshould be largely sports, citizenship,\nclothing and equipment instruction,\npersonal adjustment, personal hy\ngiene, history of military aviation\nand drills and ceremonials.\nAfter their 11 weeks of basic\ntraining, the WAPs may go to tech\nnical schools selected according to\ntheir aptitudes and preferences. The\nAir Force is emphasizing the career\naspect of the WAP.\nThere is the opportunity, for in\nstance, for a WAF who starts out as\n\"JC*\u00abp Rollin\u2019 With Not on\u201d\nFINANCING\nPRIVATE SALES\nOUR SPECIALTY!\nNOLAN\nAUTOMOBILE\nLOANS\nFararable Rates\nNo Indorsors\n1102 New York A vs N.W.\nGreyhoaad Bat Ttnaiaa)\nBE. l'.**0\n0\u00bb<\u00bb Till r.U.\na cook to move up the line eventu\nally to the position of food service\nsuperintendent\u201d with the rank of\nwarrant Officer and pay equivalent\nto that of a major.\nOr, if she prefers another food\nline, she may become a meatcutter\nsuperintendent, with the same rank.\nThe advent of the WAP to Lack\nland was met with enthusiasm by\ntheir brother \u201cairmen.\u201d The non\ncommissioned men officers built a\nhandsome noncommissioned WAF\nofficers\u2019 Club, tastefully'furnished in\nrose and green.\nIt was rumored that men KPs\nwere being paid as much as $5 by\ntheir fellows in exchange for the\nprivilege of working in the WAF\nmess.\nEconomists Predict\nRecession Next Year\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nNEW YORK, Oct. 23.\u2014A majority\nof economists polled by F. W. Dodge\nCorp., expect a business recession in\n1949. Most of these believe such an\nadjustment will be moderate while a\nsizable minority doesn't think any\nrecession is in sight next year.\nResults of the survey were re\nported today by Thomas S. Holden,\npresident of the Dodge concern, a\nfact-finding organization for the\nconstruction industry.\nOf 112 economists whose opinions\nwere obtained, Mr. Holden said, 64\nanticipate recession in 1949 and 47\nsee no such development.\nA continous decline in the cost of\nliving through next year was pre\ndicted by 46 of the economists.\nAgainst this, 21 expect the cost of\nliving index to rise during part of\nthe year, followed by a drop, and\nnine forecast a continous rise.\nWith repect to residential build\ning volume, 67 expect it to decrease\nnext year and 28 forecast an in\ncrease.\nA large volume of public construc\ntion is anticipated by 70, a smaller\ntotal by 24.\nAmericans\u2019 accumulated savings\nat the end of 1945 were $135,000,000,\n000 more than they were five years\nbefore. i\nSqueaky\u2014The Hot Water Spaniel\na*\n>/OW-W-W! WHO\\\nyUSED ALL THE\n7 HOT WATER?/\nF^h-h-h!mister^\nf YOU'D BETTER f\n\\CALL WEBSTER\u2019Sf\n3 AND ORDER A (f\nH StRVEL 1\nAUTOMATIC GA$Y\nW/ATER HEATERjj\nThe Servel Automotic Gas Water\nHeater keeps you in hot water.\nThermostat-controlled burner operates\nonly when water is below proper\ntemperature. Double-thick in'ulohon\nkeeps water hot\u2014saves fuel. Rusting,\nand leaks caused by rusting ore\neliminated by the boll-type copper tank.\nOrder your Servel Automotic Water\nHeater today. Yours for a small down\npayment ond convenient terms. In\nstallation same day vou order.\n10-YEAR GUARANTEE\nAll Models All Capacities\n\"We Will Install The Day You Coll\"\nJOHM G. WllSTIl\n627 F St. N.W. EX. 4615\n(Opp, The Hecht Co. on F St)\n\"WE KEFP YOU IN HOT W'ATER\"\nDo this:\nVNSCAtW HAN Oil Of\ntAFtTY AAIOA\nnr\nAtMQVt THi PAPT\nNiXT TO HAN PH\npr\nN 7\nPUT SPCCDY-TPIN\nIN PL* cl or PAPT\nSCPC* HAM tit MACK\ntM POSITION\nTISTID AND\nAPMOVID\nOnJtu\n150*\nMac* this Speedy-Trim in\nyour double-edge sofety racer\nand you have an idtol hbir trim\nmer far Hi* whale family. Needs n#\nadjustments. Vary handy la trim, thin, taper end shape\nth* heir. Spaady-Trim is simple end easy la us*. Will\nbe enjoyed by every member *f your family. Worth many\ntimes its price end convenience. Send for your Speedy-Trim\ntoday!\nTHE SPEEDY-TRIM CO. X\u00b0\nP O. Sox 4334. Washington 12, 0. C\nGentlemen:\nenclose S.- -Pleat* tend me pottage prepaid\n.Speedy-Trimt, at S0< each. (Ho itompt).\nNAME ....____.....\nADDRESS H-...-I\u2014.i\u2014i-111,...\u00ab>...\u25a0\u2014i\u2014\u2014\u2014\nCITt ___STATE\nD.C. Hibernians Honor\n2 National Officers;\nGifts Are Presented\nTwo District residents who were\nelected recently to national posts In\nthe Ancient Order of Hibernians\nwere honored last night at a dinner\ngiven by the Washington chapter in\nthe Catholic Daughters of America\nBuilding, Sixteenth street and Mas\nsachusetts avenue N.W.\nMore than 300 members and\nguests of the organization, many\nfrom distant parts of the country,\npaid tribute to Lt. Michael J. Dowd\nof the Metropolitan Police Depart\nment, and Miss Lillian Pay. Lt.\nDowd was elected national director\nof the order and Miss Pay national\nvice president of the ladies\u2019 auxiliary\nat the group's meeting August 6 in\nMontreal, Canada.\nNational Leaders Present.\nPresent at the affair, sponsored\nby the Commodore John Barry Divi\nsion of the Ancient Order of Hi\nbernians, were Miss Leonore Shay\nof Braddock, Pa., national president\nof the ladles\u2019 auxiliary; Miss Anna\nCarey of Trenton, N. J., past na\ne>nal president of the auxiliary, and\nartin Cook, president of the John\nBarry Division. Mr. Cook presided.\n1 Chairman of the dinner was Vinson\nA. McGarry, secretary of the\ndivision.\nAmong the gifts presented to Lt.\nDowd by Joseph Daly, a past presi-\nj dent of the local unit, was a travel\nling bag. Miss Pay received a wrist\nwatch from the organization. The\npresentation was made by Miss\nMary Cleary, past president of the\nWashiiigton auxiliary.\nCites Order's Record.\nLt. Dowd told the gathering that\n\u2018\u2018true allegiance to God and country\nhas marked every step of our order's\nprogress since it was started in the\nhills of Ireland many years ago.\u201d He\nassented the order will \"continue to\ndo its part for the freedom of Ire\nland.\u201d The society was started in\nthe United States 115 years ago and\nmore than 100 years ago in Wash\nington.\nA native of Ireland, It. Dowd came\nto Washington 30 years ago. He\nserved overseas in the Army during\nWorld War I and Joined the Metro\npolitan Police Department in July.\n1919. He lives at 1324 Rittenhouse\nstreet N.W. His wife, Mrs. Peggy\nDowd, is president of the Washing\nton auxiliary.\nMiss Fay, a native of the District,\nis associated with the National\nGeographic Society. She lives at\n2505 Thirteenth street N.W.\nBoth Lt. Dowd and Miss Fay have\nbeen members of the society for\nmany years.\nPolio Sets Record in Iowa\nDES MOINES, Oct. 23 (*>).\u2014'The\nnumber of polio cases reported in\nIowa this year has set a new all\ntime record. TTie State Health De\npartment reported today the total\ncases for 1948 had risen to 961 so\nfar.\nAero Club to Hear Dufek\nNavy Capt. George J. Dufek. com\nmander of the force that discovered\nI the Peary papers in the Artie, will\nspeak at a luncheon of the Aero\nClub of Washington at 12:30 p.m.\nTuesday at the Hotel Washington.\nFully Lined \u2018Cravenette\nGabardine\nTOPCOATS\n*24.75\ne Raglan Shoulders\ne Water Repellent\ne For Rain or Shine\nNA. 4312\n906-908 7th St. N.W.\nGirl, i, Hurt in Attack;\nStepfather Held at Tulsa\nly th\u00ab Aisociotcd Prni\nTULSA, Okla., Oct. 23.\u2014A 6-year\nold girl was in critical condition to\nday from injuries Chief of Police\nJay W. Hollinsworth said were re\nceived when she was raped aijd\nbeaten.\nThe chief said the girl\u2019s stepfather,\nbooked as Albert Edward Griffin, 30,\nof Tulsa was being held for inves\ntigation. No charges were filed.\nHe was taken into custody at a\nroad block at the outskirts of Tulsa.\nIn the wuto with him, the chief said,\nofficers found the child suffering\nfrom lacerations and bruises and\nloss of blood.\nShe was taken to a hospital where\nphysicians pronounced her condition\ncritical and said she had been\nraped.\nThe road block was established,\nChief Hollinsworth went on, at the\nrequest of police at Port Smith. Ark.\nThe Port Smith chief said the\nchild\u2019s mother, estranged from the\nstepfather, resides in California.\nThe stepfather went to Port\nSmith yesterday and visited the\nchild\u2019s grandparents, Mr. and Mrs.\nP. H. Carney.\nMr. Carney said the man acted\nfriendly then, but early today at\ntacked him and Mrs. Carney with\na metal bar, beating them into un\nconsciousness. When they regained\nconsciousness, the child was gone.\nI It\u2019s Good Business\nto buy a\nGood Business Suit\nSmithson Specialised\nNAVAL SERGE\nAnd that, gentleman, meant\na suit that not only has in\nitial eye appeal, but the\nbasic quality to stand by\nand look handsome through\nprolonged wear.\nThat's what makes this\nnaval serge by Smithson a\nprime favorite wth success\nful executives. It's sunfast,\nshine resistant. It holds its\nshape. It looks like a million\nand it's loomed especially\nfor Smithson.\nIn the classic single breasted, three\nbutton model, site\nranges from 35\nshort to 5O\u2019 stout.\nFREDERICK'S\nMen's Wear Stores\nCharre Accounts Invited\n1435 H St. N.W.\n701 H St. N.E.\nN.E. Store Open Till 9 P.M.\nLearn to Play the\nACC\u00abB\u00aeI#5i\nand have all the fun that\ngoes with knowing how. And\nit\u2019s easy to learn to play,\nyou gain skill and assure\nance in a few lessons.\nat Kitfs\n10 Lessons\nare included\nwith this fine 12-bass Accordion\n\nHere is a wonderful opportunity to purchase\na fine new accordion\u2014plus 10 private les\nsons\u2014for only $99.50. And this well-built\n12 bass accordion is an instrument you will\nbe proud to own. Has 25 treble keys and\nmetal tipped bellows. i\nonly\nACCORDION A\n.nd SQQ.50\n10 Private Lessons\nExtended budget terms available\n(between 13t